05041nam a22007815i 9780674063150DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979739984  a(OCoLC)984686848  a(OCoLC)987949090  a(OCoLC)992472079  a(OCoLC)999381777  a97806740631507 a10.4159/harvard.97806740631502doi  a(DE-B1597)178122  a(OCoLC)773265344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aMED0360002bisacsh04a614.4/72231 aHoyt, Kendall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLong Shot :bVaccines for National Defense /cKendall Hoyt. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (314 p.) :b1 halftone, 6 line illustrations, 8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tText Acronyms -- tIntroduction -- t1. Disease, Security, and Vaccines -- t2. Historical Patterns of Vaccine Innovation -- t3. Vaccine Development during World War II -- t4. Wartime Legacies -- t5. The End of an Era -- t6. Biodefense in the Twenty-First Century -- t7. The Search for Sustainable Solutions -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the twenty-first century, the United States contended with a state-run biological warfare program, bioterrorism, and a pandemic. Together, these threats spurred large-scale government demand for new vaccines, but few have materialized. A new anthrax vaccine has been a priority since the first Gulf War, but twenty years and a billion dollars later, the United States still does not have one. This failure is startling.Historically, the United States has excelled at responding to national health emergencies. World War II era programs developed ten new or improved vaccines, often in time to meet the objectives of particular military missions. Probing the history of vaccine development for factors that foster timely innovation, Kendall Hoyt discovered that vaccine innovation has been falling, not rising, since World War II. This finding is at odds with prevailing theories of market-based innovation and suggests that a collection of nonmarket factors drove mid-century innovation. Ironically, many late-twentieth-century developments that have been celebrated as a boon for innovation—the birth of a biotechnology industry and the rise of specialization and outsourcing—undercut the collaborative networks and research practices that drove successful vaccine projects in the past.Hoyt’s timely investigation teaches important lessons for our efforts to rebuild twenty-first-century biodefense capabilities, especially when the financial payback for a particular vaccine is low, but the social returns are high.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE  MEDICINE 2012z9783110293807oZDB-23-DME08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET MEDIZIN 2012z9783110293791oZDB-23-DMD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406315040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674063150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674063150.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BAC